<paper id="1589679581"><title>Identity-based Conference Key Distribution Systems</title><year>1987</year><authors><author org="Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corporation" id="2143259014">Kenji Koyama</author><author org="Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corporation" id="2130187483">Kazuo Ohta</author></authors><n_citation>68</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1569083856</reference><reference>1589034595</reference><reference>1996360405</reference><reference>2012168171</reference><reference>2156186849</reference><reference>2203317094</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48184-2_13</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.62748">Key distribution</keyword><keyword weight="0.48163">Complete graph</keyword><keyword weight="0.41601">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.45882">Finite field</keyword><keyword weight="0.54281">Authentication</keyword><keyword weight="0.46481">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.50418">Identification (information)</keyword><keyword weight="0.46232">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.41983">Logarithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.44648">A* search algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.49045">Factoring</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>This paper proposes identity-based key distribution systems for generating a common secret conference key for two or more users. Users are connected in a ring, a complete graph, or a star network. Messages among users are authenticated using each useru0027s identification information. The security of the proposed systems is based on the difficulty of both factoring large numbers and computing discrete logarithms over large finite fields.</abstract></paper>